Ejemplo rasteriza¶

This notebook is going to show how to create a map using geopandas and how to reduce the file size of the obtained figure.

In [22]:
import os
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib import cm
import warnings
import contextily as ctx
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

Create the map¶

To create the map geopandas already has a implementation to do it, so this example only is going to show a add a map under the the map created in geopandas.

Load data¶

The file to be loaded has the job to house ratio in 500 metters. It was created by pablo.

Let us divide the geopandas into 5 different dataframes an plot them each in distinct figures.

In [11]:
entropia_metrop_cdmx_df =gpd.read_file('../data/entropia_manzanas_vecin_500m_2012.zip')
qu = entropia_metrop_cdmx_df['entropia'].quantile(q=[0,.2,.4,.6,.8,1.0])
Q1 = entropia_metrop_cdmx_df[(entropia_metrop_cdmx_df['entropia'] >= qu[0]) & (entropia_metrop_cdmx_df['entropia'] < qu[0.2]) ]
Q2 = entropia_metrop_cdmx_df[(entropia_metrop_cdmx_df['entropia'] >= qu[0.2]) & (entropia_metrop_cdmx_df['entropia'] < qu[0.4]) ]
Q3 = entropia_metrop_cdmx_df[(entropia_metrop_cdmx_df['entropia'] >= qu[0.4]) & (entropia_metrop_cdmx_df['entropia'] < qu[0.6]) ]
Q4 = entropia_metrop_cdmx_df[(entropia_metrop_cdmx_df['entropia'] >= qu[0.6]) & (entropia_metrop_cdmx_df['entropia'] < qu[0.8]) ]
Q5 = entropia_metrop_cdmx_df[(entropia_metrop_cdmx_df['entropia'] >= qu[0.8]) & (entropia_metrop_cdmx_df['entropia'] < qu[1.0]) ]

In [35]:
def convert_bytes(size, unit=None):
    if unit == "KB":
        return print('File size: ',  str(round(size / 1024, 3)) ,  ' Kilobytes')
    elif unit == "MB":
        return print('File size: ' + str(round(size / (1024 * 1024), 3)) + ' Megabytes')
    elif unit == "GB":
        return print('File size: ' + str(round(size / (1024 * 1024 * 1024), 3)) + ' Gigabytes')
    else:
        return print('File size: ' + str(size) + ' bytes')

Ps2pd¶

As we can see the resulting file size if large, therefore lets reduce the size of it using the ps2pdf tool, this is a fast way to reduce the resulting image but will lose resolution and quality, ps2pdf uses under the hood ghostscript so we can pass the arguments acording to the ghost parammeters here we only will show 1 parameter and the result of it.

In [40]:
! ps2pdf -dPDFSETTINGS=/screen ../output/test_1.pdf ../output/test_1_screen.pdf

Sometimes the ps2pdf rotates the image to avoid the rotation use the parameter -dAutoRotatePages=/None or if you want to rotate use the correspondig paraameter to do it.

Lets us check how the image was reduce.

In [47]:
bit_size = os.path.getsize('../output/test_1_screen.pdf')
convert_bytes(bit_size,"KB" )
convert_bytes(bit_size,'MB' )

File size:  9606.604  Kilobytes
File size: 9.381 Megabytes

The -dPDFSETTINGS parameter has several options but here we only goint to revise the following

  • -dPDFSETTINGS=/screen
  • -dPDFSETTINGS=/ebook
  • -dPDFSETTINGS=/printer
  • -dPDFSETTINGS=/prepress
  • -dPDFSETTINGS=/default

This options reduce the size of the images the difference between them are the resulting size and quality. The screen reduce the image an leve it optimize for a screeen reolution, the others optimize for ebook, printer, and prepress respectively. The default parameter is to be optimize for several devices.

In [48]:
! ps2pdf -dPDFSETTINGS=/ebook ../output/test_1.pdf ../output/test_1_ebook.pdf
! ps2pdf -dPDFSETTINGS=/printer ../output/test_1.pdf ../output/test_1_printer.pdf
! ps2pdf -dPDFSETTINGS=/prepress ../output/test_1.pdf ../output/test_1_prepress.pdf
! ps2pdf -dPDFSETTINGS=/default ../output/test_1.pdf ../output/test_1_default.pdf

The matplotlib¶

Also there is a way to reduce the image size using matplotlib directly. This will result im better image quality, but with a big size.

In [57]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots( figsize=(8, 12))
# axs = axs.ravel()

Q1.plot(ax = axs, column= 'entropia' , color= colors(5), alpha= .5,  rasterized=True)
Q2.plot(ax = axs, column= 'entropia' , color= colors(4), alpha= .5,  rasterized=True)
Q3.plot(ax = axs, column= 'entropia' , color= colors(3), alpha= .5,  rasterized=True)
Q4.plot(ax = axs, column= 'entropia' , color= colors(2), alpha= .5,  rasterized=True)
Q5.plot(ax = axs, column= 'entropia' , color= colors(1), alpha= .5,  rasterized=True)

ctx.add_basemap(axs, source=ctx.providers.CartoDB.Positron, crs = Q1.crs)
fig.savefig('../output/test_3.pdf', dpi=600,  bbox_inches='tight')
